    <!-- Lesson 1 (A1) - 1.01 -->
    <string name="lesson101_title">Articles\n(the – a/an)</string>
    <string name="lesson101_title_short">Articles</string>
    <string name="lesson101_text01">
        \tArticles are words that define a noun as <b>specific</b> or <b>unspecific</b>.
        There are two articles in English:
        \n\n\t<b>a (an)</b> – unspecific
        \n\t<b>the</b> – specific
    </string>
    <string name="lesson101_phrase01" translatable="false">I want <b>the apple</b></string>
    <string name="lesson101_translation01">I want (this) apple</string>
    <string name="lesson101_phrase02" translatable="false">I want <b>an apple</b></string>
    <string name="lesson101_translation02">I want (one, any) apple</string>
    <string name="lesson101_text02">
        \t<b>the</b> - comes from the word \'<b>this</b>\'. <b>a (an)</b> -
        comes from the word \'<b>one 1</b>\'.
        \n\n\t<b>When is \'a\' and when is \'an\'?</b>
        \n\n\tIt\'s simple, if the word (noun) begins with a vowel <i>(a, e, o, etc.)</i>,
        then we use <b>an</b>, if a consonant <i>(b, c, d, etc.)</i> we use <b>a</b>.
    </string>
    <string name="lesson101_text03">
        a car\na table\na chair\nan elephant\nan orange
    </string>
    <string name="lesson101_text04">
        \tWe <b>don\'t</b> use articles when we use:
        \n\n1. numeral — (2) <b>two</b> cats
        \n2. possessive pronoun — <b>my</b> cat
        \n3. demonstrative pronouns <b>this, that</b> – this car/that cat
        \n4. negative particle NO - I have <b>no</b> cat
    </string>



    <!-- Lesson 2 (A1) - 1.02 -->
    <string name="lesson102_title">Plural nouns \n(-s, -es)</string>
    <string name="lesson102_title_short">Plural nouns</string>
    <string name="lesson102_phrase01" translatable="false">a book - two books</string>
    <string name="lesson102_translation01"/>
    <string name="lesson102_text01">\tFor most words, the plural is formed by adding <b>-s</b>
        at the end:</string>
    <string name="lesson102_text02">
        a car – car<b>s</b>
        \na cake – cake<b>s</b>
        \na dog – dog<b>s</b>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson102_text03">
        \t 1. If the singular noun ends in <b>-s</b>, <b>-ss</b>, <b>-sh</b>, <b>-ch</b>, <b>-x</b>,
        or <b>-z</b>, add <b>-es</b> to the end to make it plural:
    </string>
    <string name="lesson102_text04">
        a bo<b>x</b> – box<b>es</b>
        \na wat<b>ch</b> – watch<b>es</b>
	    \na dre<b>ss</b> – dress<b>es</b>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson102_text05">
        \t2. If the singular noun ends in <b>‑y</b> and
    </string>
    <string name="lesson102_text06">
        - the letter before the <b>-y</b> is a <u>vowel</u>, simply add an <b>-s</b>
        to make it plural:
		\n\na b<u>o</u>y – boy<b>s</b>\n
	    \n- the letter before the <b>-y</b> is a <u>consonant</u>, change the ending to <b>‑ies</b>
        to make the noun plural:
		\n\na sto<u>r</u>y – stor<b>ies</b>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson102_text07">
        \t3. If the nouns is ending in <b>–f</b> or <b>–fe</b>, it often changes in <b>–ves</b>:
    </string>
    <string name="lesson102_text08">
        a wol<b>f</b> – wol<b>ves</b>
	    \na wi<b>fe</b> – wi<b>ves</b>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson102_text09">
        \t4. There are exceptions that have <b>NO rules</b>:
    </string>
    <string name="lesson102_text10">
        child – children
	    \nman – men
	    \nwoman – women
	    \ntooth – teeth
	    \nmouse – mice
	    \ndeer – deer
    </string>



    <!-- Lesson 3 (A1) - 1.03 -->
    <string name="lesson103_title">Pronouns \n( I, my, me,…)</string>
    <string name="lesson103_title_short">Pronouns</string>
    <string name="lesson103_text01">
        \t <b>Subject Pronouns</b> answer the question <b>who?</b> - I, you, he, she, it, we, they.
    </string>
    <string name="lesson103_text02">
        \t <b>Object pronouns</b> are those pronouns that receive the action in a sentence.
        They answer the question <b>whom?</b> – me, you, him, her, it, us, them.
    </string>
    <string name="lesson103_phrase01">I helped <b>him</b></string>
    <string name="lesson103_translation01"/>
    <string name="lesson103_phrase02">Come to <b>me</b></string>
    <string name="lesson103_translation02"/>
    <string name="lesson103_phrase03">She sees <b>me</b></string>
    <string name="lesson103_translation03"/>
    <string name="lesson103_phrase04">Look at <b>them</b></string>
    <string name="lesson103_translation04"/>
    <string name="lesson103_phrase05">He loves <b>her</b></string>
    <string name="lesson103_translation05"/>
    <string name="lesson103_text03">
        \t <b>Possessive pronouns</b> show that something belongs to someone.
        They answer the question <b>whose?</b> – my, your, his, her, its, our, their.
    </string>
    <string name="lesson103_phrase06">This is <b>my</b> <i>book</i>,
        and that is <b>your</b> <i>book</i>.</string>
    <string name="lesson103_translation06"/>
    <string name="lesson103_text04">
        \t <b>Possessive</b> pronouns have an <b>independent</b> form, in order <b>not to repeat</b>
        the noun
    </string>
    <string name="lesson103_phrase07">This is <b>my</b> <i>book</i>,
        and that is <b>yours.</b></string>
    <string name="lesson103_translation07"/>
    <string name="lesson103_text05">Here is an <b>independent</b> form table:</string>
    <string name="lesson103_text06">Let\'s go to practice!</string>



    <!-- Lesson 4 (A1) - 1.04 -->
    <string name="lesson104_title">Simple Tenses \n(Present, Future, Past)</string>
    <string name="lesson104_title_short">Simple Tenses</string>
    <string name="lesson104_text01">
         \t In this topic, we will look at how <b>Simple Tenses</b> are formed
        <i>(Present Simple, Future Simple and Past Simple)</i>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson104_text02">
        <i>didn’t = short form of ‘did not’
        \ndon’t = short form of ‘do not’
        \ndoesn’t = short form of ‘does not’</i>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson104_text03">
        Take the verb <b>work</b> for example:
    </string>
    <string name="lesson104_text04">
        <b>Present Simple</b>
        \n<i>- Positive:</i>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase01">I work</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation01"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase02">She work<b>s</b></string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation02"/>
    <string name="lesson104_text_negative"><i>- Negative:</i></string>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase03">I <b>don’t</b> work</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation03"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase04">She <b>doesn’t</b> work</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation04"/>
    <string name="lesson104_text_question"><i>- Question:</i></string>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase05"><b>Do</b> you work? </string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation05"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase06"><b>Does</b> she work?</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation06"/>
    <string name="lesson104_text05">
        <b>Future Simple</b>
        \n<i>- Positive:</i>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase07">I <b>will</b> work</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation07"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase08">She <b>will</b> work</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation08"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase09">I <b>will not</b> work</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation09"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase10">She <b>will not</b> work</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation10"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase11"><b>Will</b> you work?</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation11"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase12"><b>Will</b> she work?</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation12"/>
    <string name="lesson104_text06">
        <b>Past Simple</b>
        \n<i>- Positive:</i>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase13">I work<b>ed</b></string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation13"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase14">She work<b>ed</b></string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation14"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase15">I <b>didn’t</b> work</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation15"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase16">She <b>didn’t</b> work</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation16"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase17"><b>Did</b> you work?</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation17"/>
    <string name="lesson104_phrase18"><b>Did</b> she work?</string>
    <string name="lesson104_translation18"/>
    <string name="lesson104_text07">
        <i>You can try it yourself with other verbs for memorization</i>
    </string>

    <!-- Lesson 5 (A1) - 1.05 -->
    <string name="lesson105_title">Present Simple</string>
    <string name="lesson105_title_short">Present Simple</string>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase01"><b>I read</b> books</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation01"/>
    <string name="lesson105_text01">
        \t We need to use the <b>Present Simple</b> a lot in English,
        so it is really important to understand it well.
        \n\t Present Simple is very simple. Only in the 3rd person singular<i>(he/she/it)</i> we add an <b>-s</b>
    </string>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase02">I love you</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation02"/>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase03">He love<b>s</b> her</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation03"/>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase04">I see you</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation04"/>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase05">She see<b>s</b> them</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation05"/>
    <string name="lesson105_text02">
        \t For the negative form we add <b>don’t</b> or
        <b>doesn’t</b><i>(for 3rd person singular)</i>:
    </string>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase06">She <b>doesn’t</b> love him</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation06"/>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase07">I <b>don’t</b> see you</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation07"/>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase08">You <b>don’t</b> know me</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation08"/>
    <string name="lesson105_text03">
        \t For the questions we use <b>Do</b> or
        <b>Does</b><i>(for 3rd person singular)</i>:
    </string>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase09">Where <b>do</b> you work?</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation09"/>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase10"><b>Do</b> you love her?</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation10"/>
    <string name="lesson105_phrase11"><b>Does</b> he speak Russian?</string>
    <string name="lesson105_translation11"/>
    <string name="lesson105_text04">
        Now, practice your knowledge!
    </string>

